{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_huxley_ver01/data/sn84020630/00416150266/1907110801/0912.xml":{"full_text":"page two\nFRIDAY, NOVEMBER 8; 1907.\nSANTA FE NEW MEXICAN.\nTHE NEW MEXICAN PRINTING COMPANY, PUBLISHERS.\nVIAX. FROST, Editor. JOHN K. STAUFFER, Sec'y-Treas.\nEDWIN F. COARD, City Editor.\nEntered as Second Class Matter at the Santa Fe Postofflce\nRATES OF SUBSCRIPTION.\nDally, per week, by carrier .20\nDally, per month, by carrier 75\nOaily, per month, by mall .65\ntally, per year, by mall 7.00\nDally, six months, by mail 3.75\nWeekly, per year 2.00\nWeekly, six months 1.00\nWeekly, per quarter 75\nOFFICIAL PAPER OF SANTA FE COUNTY.\nThe New Mexican is the oldest n ewspaper In New Mexico. It Is sent to\nevery postofflce in the Territory, an d has a large and growing circulation\namong the intelligent and progresslv e people of the Southwest.\nUMION\nCURRENCY REFORM LAWS NEC\nESSARY.\nUnder the heading, \"A Better Cur\nrency System Needed,\" the Pueblo\nChieftain discusses the needs of the\ncountry in that respect very sensibly\nand very timely and expresses the\nviews and opinions of the solid and\nsteady people, especially of tliose mod\nerately well to do, who work for a\nliving and for a competency, and who\nare in the great majority in the coun\ntry. The Chieftain's position is very well\ntaken and gives the question plainly\nand undisguised for discussion and\nconsideration. There is talk of an ex\ntra session for the purpose of action\nby congress thereon and If this extra\nsession does not take place the sub\nject must necessarily be disposed of\nat the regular session. It Is one of the\ngreatest importance to 'the country.\nSays the Chieftain:\n\"One result of the recent stock\ngamblers' panic in New York and its\nconsequences to the rest of the coun\ntry should be a thorough revision of\nthe currency laws, and a provision for\na larger volume of money to meet the\nrequirements of business. The present\nsituation la one that reflects disgrace\nupon congress, which is the responsi\nble author of our monetary laws, and\nwhen manufacturers in large cities are\ncompelled to pay their employers from\nchecks because no money is to be had\nfrom the banks it does not require any\nargument to prove that there Is some\nthing wrong with the methods by\nwhich money is supplied for business\nuses.\n\"There is no doubt that currency re\nform will be an important part of the\nwork of the next Congress and a\nstrong effort will be made to secure\ncongressional approval for the asset\ncurrency plan proposed by the Ameri\ncan Bankers' Association committee.\nThe principle of this plan Is that\nbanks which are known to be solvent\nmay Issue a limited amount of notes\nbased upon their assets, without the\nrequirement of a deposit of govern\nment bonds in the national treasury.\nBut while this plan received the ap\nproval of the National Bankers' con\nvention, It .is significant that it Is op\nposed by many of the state bankers'\nassociations. Nebraska went on record\nagainst the plan last year. Minnesota,\nWisconsin and Indiana declared\nagainst it this year, the banks of the\nlast named state resolving that 'while\nwe are strongly In favor of some well\nsecured method to relieve monetary\nstringencies that will not produce In\nflation, yet we are unalterably opposed\nto any change in our currency that\ndoes not afford absolute security;\nhence we do not look with favor upon\nthe plan proposed by the American\nBankers' association committee.'\n\"The two points that should be in\nsisted upon in any plan of currency\nreform are absolute security and that\nthe national credit should not be loan\ned to private advantage.\n\"Thus far no really satisfactory plan\nof currency reform has been made\npublic, but we cannot doubt that when\nthe matter comes before congress for\nconsideration some system will be\nfound by which sufficient money can\nbe provided to do business without\ncompelling the banks to hold large\namounts of idle cash In their vaults\nfor much the largest part of the time.\"\nTHE RESULT OF THE NICHOL8\nTRIAL.\nThe acquittal of Frank R. Nichols\nin the United States court of the west\nern district of Pennsylvania at Pitts\nburg yesterday of indictments charg\ning complicity and conspiracy In the\nwrecking of the Enterprise National\nBank of Allegheny after twenty min\nutes deliberation by the jury will have\nthe salutary effect of showing to the\npeople of New Mexico that the accusa\ntions and charges made by Democrats\nand yellow sheets In this territory and\nby political enemies that Delegate W.\nH. Andrews was partly to blame for\nthe bank's disaster and for the suicide\nof T. Lee Clark, its cashier, and had\nimproper and dishonest connections\nwith the dead cashier of the bank are\nabsolutely untrue and libels in the\ntruest sense of the word. Because\nNichols had been private secretary to\nDelegate Andrews while the latter was\nin business and In politics in Pitts\nhurg and was thereafter an employe of\nthe bank and had financial transac\ntions with it la which the delegate's\nname appeared as the endorser of\nnnto the enemies of the lat\nter made unscrupulous and shameful\nuse of tbt connection and Invented\nand published broadcast charges and\naccusation for the purpose of Injur\ning Delegate Andrews, lowering his\nstanding with the people, destroying\nhis usefulness nnd to defeat him for\nthe nomination and election last year.\nThe trial was an exhaustive one and\nhad Nichols been guilty or had Dele\ngate Andrews in any manner been dis\nhonestly or Improperly connected with\nthe financial transactions of the closed\nbank the trial would have certainly\nbrought these out fully. As it is the\nfact that Nichols was declared not\nguilty after a thorough and Impartial\ntrial in which the prosecution was\nconducted by most able counsel for\nthe government and that the jury de\nliberated but twenty minutes upou the\ncase is a clean and clear vindication\nof Delegate Andrews in this matter\nand even his bitterest and most vindic\ntive enemies will be no longer able to\nuse the case as a club to hit him po\nlitically or financially. After all right\nand justice prevails in due course of\ntime and the case at issue is in point,\nDelegate Andrews did not rush into\nprint but bided his time feeling that\nJustice would fully vindicate his\ncourse as far as the Enterprise bank\nand T. Lee Clark were concerned. This\nis now accomplished and the dele\ngate's many, many thousands of\nfriends and well-wishers in New\nMexico aro glad of it. They never had\nany doubts of the result.\nNEW MEXICO FINANCIALLY\nSOLID.\nThe banks of New Mexico from all\nindications appear to be In good con\ndition and not at all afraid of the\nfinancial flurries which have been dis\nturbing New York City and other fin\nancial centers. The people of New\nMexico as a whole have enjoyed great\nprosperity during the Republican ad\nministrations in the past ten years\nand the leading industries of the ter\nritory, live stock raising, agriculture\nand mining, have flourished. Railroad\nbuilding which has been going on to\na considerable extent during recent\nyears In the territory has aided ma\nterially In putting money into the\npeople's pockets and more or lesR\ntherefore into the banks. As a rule\nthe people of the territory are frugal\nand careful and not Inclined to be\nspendthrifts. \"While they are not great\nmoney makers they are good money\nsavers. This characteristic comes in\nvery hardy now and means much for\nthe stability and solid standing of the\nfinancial institutions of the territory.\nTo be sure there are some pessimists\nwho are propheslng dire financial dis\naster in the near future. But so there\nhave been and are today pessimists\nwho have prophesied and fortold the\ndestruction of the world at numer\nous times. There is so much financial\nsolidity in the territory and the sav\nings of the people have been so great\nthat it is proper to say that the finan\ncial future holds no disasters In store\nfor New Mexico.\nIn yesterday's Issue the New Mexi\ncan announced that another batch of\neighteen pensions had been granted to\nNew Mexico veterans owing to the\ncareful and diligent attention given\nthe claims of worthy old soldiers, es\npecially of the Civil War, by Delegate\nW. H. Andrews. More pensions have\nbeen secured since Delegate Andrews\ntook office as the representative of\nthe people of New Mexico than ever be\nfore since the pension laws became\noperative. That the proof of the pud\nding is in the eating is very applicable\nto this matter. The 'proof that Dele\ngate Andrews is a conscientious and\nhard working delegate is shown in the\nfact of his many accomplishments for\nNew Mexico, the securing of pensions\nnot at all being one of the last or\nleast.\nIt is gratifying to learn that the gov\nernment of Japan has no desire what\never for a row with the United States,\nbut that all the Japanese desire is\npeace and good will between the two\ncountries. This expression at this time\non the part of the Mikado's govern\nment is very timely and will be re\ncelved with much approval and com\nmendation. For fifty years the Unit\ned States has been a firm and staunch\nfriend of Nippon and its people and\nit is certainly the hope of the admin\nistration and the people of this coun\ntry that nothing of sufficiently serious\ncharacter to mar these friendly and\ncordial relations will ever occur.\nWELCOME TO THE EL PA80AN8.\nThe New Mexican extends a hearty\nand sincere welcome to the breezy,\nbright and aggressive business men\nof the city of El Paso who visited\nSanta Fe this evening and abided\nwithin its gates for a few hours for\nthe purpose of becoming better ac\nquainted, establishing friendly rela\ntions, personal and business, and for\nseeing for themselves what there is to\nthe capital city of New Mexico, so\nfar in their journeys through the Sun\nshine Territory they have had very en\njoyable times and have met with very\ncord'al and genial receptions. They\nhave made a very pleasing and good\nImpression In the cities and towns\nwhich they have visited and of course\nthis Hll be the case here. Business\nmen and citizens of Santa Fe general\nly will do what they can to make their\nstay of a few hours here a charming,\npleasant and pleasureable occasion\nworth remembering for many a month\nto come. It is regretted that their so\njourn here can not be made of longer\nduration but under the circumstances,\nconsidering that they are very busy\nmen who have much to do at home\nthis will have to do, although It can\nnot be doubted that a longer time\nspent here would be more profitable\nand more satisfactory to all concern\ned. However small favors thankfully\nreceived and larger ones in proportion.\nThe business men and citizens with\nthe New Mexican hope and trust that\nthey will enjoy their visit here to the\nfullest extent and take home with\nthem to the enterprising city which\nthey represent favorable and pleasant\nopinions and a fair knowledge of the\nconditions and resources of the cities\nand towns which they have honored\nwith their visits. May the cordial good\nwill and the genuine friendly feeling\nwhich will be engendered by this trip\nbetween the citizens and business men\nof the Pass City and the citizens and\nbusiness men of those portions of New\nMexico which they visit continue and\ngrow in volume and strength, for all\ntime to the pleasure, profit and bene\nfit of all concerned.\nPROFESSIONAL CARDS\nI\n3KR\nATTORNEYS-AT-LAW.\nMAX. FR08T,\nAttorney at Law.\nSanta Fe New Mexico\nPresident Roosevelt will certainly\nstrike the right keynote In recom\nmending to the COth Congress a mod\nification and reduction of the tariff\non print paper. The American paper\ntrust is one of the greatest and worst\nmonopolies in the country and its ra\npacity and gluttonness voracity must be\ncurtailed. He will strike another very\npopular chord in the right direction\nby instructing the attorney general to\ninvestigate the doings of the nefarious\ntrust and see to it that its constant\nand many violations of the anti-trust\nlaw cease. Neither the president, nor\nthe Congress, nor the attorney general\ncan act too speedily, or strongly In the\nmatter.\nAgain the Dutch have taken Holland\nand the Democrats carried the sov\nereign 6tate of Mississippi for everv-\nthing in sight last Tuesday. As the\nRepublicans put up no ticket thoy had\nan easy time. Between cooked ud elec\ntion laws, the disfranchisement of the\ncolored voters, and the shot sun Dollcy\nthe Democratic bosses of that state\nhave a sure and secure hold upon the\noffices. The dear people are not In\nit.\nDespite the faction strife in Repub\nlican ranks In New Jersey late and\ncomplete returns show that John F.\nFort, the Republican candidate for\ngovernor, was elected by a safe ma\njority and that the coming state leg\nislature will be Republican which in\nsures the election of a Republican to\nthe coming vacancy In the Senate.\nThe Republicans of the state did bet\nter than was expected.\nThe Kansas City Journal Is of the\nopinion that Hughes and Fairbanks\nwill not make the homestretch next\nyear In the presidential race, ,and\nquaintly remarks editorially:\n\"Governor Hughes of New York is\nsaid to bo a very cold man. It would\nrequire a strong imagination to pic\nture Hughes and Fairbanks cominc\ndown the homestretch in a hot finish.\"\nAlthough the administration helped\nthem a great deal yet many of the\nWall street financiers and trust mag\nnates have no liking for President\nRoosevelt. They are ungrateful. The\nadministration helped bridge over the\nchasm of financial destruction, and\nthey should remember that the Presi\ndent is the head of the present na\ntlonal administration.\nThe $25,000,000 put up by J. Pier\npont Morgan, John D. Rockefeller and\nother great financiers to help the fin\nancial situation in New York three\nweeks ago on its feet may be \"tainted\"\nmoney but just then and there no\nbody inquired into this. Circumstances\nalter cases. Even the most tainted of\nmoney comes in very handy when\npeci le need it.\nThe longer they practice law in New\nYork the more they know. One of the\njudges in that great state has Just de\ncided that a married woman has no\nright to throw dishes at her husband.\nMassachusetts gave a majority of\nnearly 100,000 for the Republican\nstate ticket last Tuesday and the Leg\nislative Assembly will also be solidly\nRepublican. The people of the Old\nBay state evidently know which side\ntheir bread Is buttered on politically.\nG. W. PRICHi ,iD,\nAttorney and Counselor at Law.\nPractices In all the District Courts\nand gives special attention to cases\nbefore the Territorial Supreme Court\nOffice: Laughlin Blk., Santa Fe, N. M.\nBENJAMIN M. READ\nAttorney at Law.\nSanta Fe, New Mexico.\nOffice: Sena Block, Palac Avenue.\nWILLIAM H. H. LLEWELLYN,\nAttorney at Law.\nLas Cruces, New Mexico.\nUnited States District Attorney.\nA. W. POLLARD,\nAttorney at Law.\nDistrict Attorney, Luna County.\nDemlng New Mexico,\nKentucky went Republican last\nTuesday for the governor and state\noffices by a handsome majority. With\na fair vote and a free count the un\nterrifled Democracy and Bryanlsm are\nnot as strong in the \"Solid South\" as\nthey were a few years as;o.\nFinancial panic or no financial panic\nthe beef trust has not reduced the\nprice of meat\nEDWARD C. WADE,\nAttorney at Law.\nPractice in the Supreme and dis\ntrict Courts of the Territory, in the\nProbate Courts and before the U. S.\nSurveyor General and U. S. Land\nOffices. Las Cruces, N. M.\nE. C. ABBOTT,\nAttorney at Law.\nPractices in the District and Su\npreme Courts. Prompt and careful\nattention given to all business.\nSanta Fe New Mexico.\nA. B. RENEHAN,\nPractices In the Supreme and Dis\ntrict Courts. Mining and Land Law\na Specialty. Office in Catron Block.\nSanta Fe, N. M.\nCHA3. F. EASLEY,\n(Late Surveyor General.)\nAttorney at Law.\nSanta Fe New Mexico..\nLand and Mining Business a Specialty.\nGEORGE B. BARBER,\nAttorney and Counselor at Law,\nLincoln, Lincoln County, New Mexico.\nPractice in the District Court and\nSupreme Courts of the Territory.\nPrompt Attention Given to All\nBusiness.\nFRANK W. CLANCY,\nAttorney at Law.\nDistrict Attorney for Second Judicial\nDistrict.\nPractices in the District Court and\n(he Supremo Court of the Territory;\nalso before the United States Supreme\nCourt In Washington.\nAlbuquerque, New Mexico.\nH. B. HOLT,\nAttorney at Law.\nLas Cruces, New Mexico.\nPractices In the District Courts as\nwell as before the 8uprem Court of\nthe Territory.\nMARK B. THOMPSON\nAttorney-at-Law\nDistrict Attorney, Eighth District,\nnona Ana. Lincoln and Otero Coun\nLas Cruces New Mexico\nHARVIE DUVAL,\nAttorney at Law.\nLand, Mining and Corporation Law ex\nclusively. Practice in ail the District\nCourts and Supreme Court. Special\nattention to perfecting titles and or\nganizing and financing land and min\ning properties.\nOffice, Laughlin Bldg., Santa Fe, N. M.\nH. M. DOUGHERTY,\nAttorney and Counsellor at Law.\nPractices in the Supreme and District\nCourts of the Territory.\nOffice, Socorro. New Mexico.\nCATRON GORTNER.\nAttorneys and Counsellors at Law,\nCatron Block.\nSanta Fe New Mexico.\nJOHN K. 8TAUFFER,\nNotary Public.\nOffice with the New Mexicaa Print\ning Co., Santa Fe, New Mexico.\nROMAN L. BACA,\nReal Estate and Mines.\nSpanish Translator, Notary Public.\nOffice Griffin Bldg.,- Washington\nAve., Santa Fe, N. M.\nOSTEOPATHY.\nOR. CHARLES A. WHEELON,\nOsteopath.\nNo. 103 Palace Ave.\nSuccessfully treats acute and chronic\ndiseases without drugs or medicines.\nNo charge for Consultation.\nHours: 9-12 m., 2-6 p. ro. 'Phone 156\nCONY T. BROWN,\nMining Engineer. -Secretary\nand Treasurer New Mexico\n8chool of Mines.\nSocorrc New Mexico.\nCORBET A 8MYTHE,\nCivil, Mining and Hydraulic Engineers\nAssaying and General Contracting.\nU. 8. Deputy Mineral Surveyors.\nEast side Plaza. Santa Fe, N. 11\nDAVID M. WHITE, C. E.\n(Late Territorial Engineer.)\nIrrigation, Water Supply, Railroad\nand Bridge Building.\n8anta Fe, New Mexico.\nE. W. HART. -Architects.\nPlans Specifications and Supervision\nAddress.\nRooms 5 and 6 Pioneer Bldg.\nEa9t Lsb Vegas,\nN. M.\nTHE FIRST pTIOJilAL BAM\nOF SANTA ;FE.\nThe oldest banking Institutio n In New Mexico. Established In 1870.\nRUFUS J. PALEN, President. JOHN H. VAUGHN, Cashier.\nLEVI A. HUGHES, Vice Presl dent. ALFRED H. BRODHEAD,\nAssistant Cashier.\nCapital 8tock, $150,000.\n8urplus and Undivided Profits $63,600.\nTransacts a general banking business In all Its branches. Loans\nmoney on the most favorable t erms on all kinds of personal and col\nlateral security. Buys and sell s bonds and stocks In all markets for\nIts customers. Buys and sells domestic and foreign exchange and\nmakes telegraphic transfers of money to all ports of the civilized\nworld on as liberal terms as are given by any money transmitting\nagency, public or private. Interest allowed on time deposits at the\nrate of three per cent per annum, on six months' or year's term.\nLiberal advances made on cons Ignments of live stock and products.\nThe bank executes all orders of Its patrons In the banking line, and\naims to extend to them as liberal treatment In all respects, as It con\nconsistent with safety and the principles of sound banking. Safety De\nposit boxes for rent. The patronage of the public is respectfully solicited.\nTHE PALACE HOTEL\nWILLIAM VAUGHN, Pf opt.\na-.\nOne of the Best Hotels in the West\nCuisine and Table Service Unexcelled.\nLarge Sample Rooms for Commercial Travelers.\nSanta Fe, New Mexico Washington Avenue\nLACOME GABLB, Proprietors.\nQ THE\nL\nA\nI\nR\nE\nHOTEL\nnr IT! Mia...\nM\nI\nAmerican and European Flan. Commodious Sample Rooms. 8team\nHeated. Electric Lighted. Every Room a Good Ore. Short Order\nDepartment Open Day and Night. Press the Batten we do the rest.\ne\nTHE NEW MEXICO\nCOLLEGE OF AGRICULTURE\nAND MECHANIC ARTS.\nOCTOBER 28TH TO MARCH 1ST.\nA complete and thoroughly practical course of instruction .In Field\nCrops, Dairying, Farm Machinery, Farm Mechanics, Fruit Growing,\nVegetable Growing, Livestock and Elementary Agriculture, Cooking,\nHome Sanitation, Sewing, Fancy Needlework.\nFOUR months beginning October 28th. Prepared for those who\ncannot attend school the full year but who are free during November,\nDecember January and February. Course open to any one over fifteen\nyears of age.\nFor further Information address,\nLUTHER FOSTER, President\nP. O.) Agricultural College, N. M.\nBERGERE I IIS MCE BY COtPUIV\nGENERAL AGENTS FOR NEW MEXICO FOR\nPEIIII MUTUAL LIFE INSURANCE COMPANY\nOF PHILADELPHIA, PA.\nPurely a Mutual Insurance Company.\nRational Surety Co., of flew York\nCourt Fidelity and Public Official Bonds Lowest Rates.\nStrong Line of Fire Insurance Companies.\nPalace Avenue\nSANTA FE, NEW MEXICO\nDIAMONDS H. C, VOWT7 WATCHES\nRI0HT PBIC\" MFYIfAN Pll IfiPFF\nRIGHT GOODS Fitted by Up-to\nDate Methods\nRIGHT SERVICE\nJEWELERY\nCUT GLASS, CHINA AND SILVERWARE\n141 8an Frar.rtsc 81 Bants Ts. N.J","height":"29780","width":"19196"}}
